  "opinion": "As an 85-year-old woman living in Los Angeles, I've seen many health crises come and go, but the COVID-19 pandemic was something different. Dealing with discussions about healthcare and COVID vaccines can be tricky, especially at my age, where I'm more vulnerable and have lived through times when medical advice wasn't always so clear. I'm retired now, with only a primary school education, but I've learned a lot from life experiences and my husband, who comes from a more educated background—his mother had a master's degree, while my parents had lower levels of schooling. This has taught me to value different perspectives. I'm agnostic, so I don't rely on religious beliefs for health decisions, but I do think it's important to listen to science and doctors. Being depressed sometimes makes these conversations harder, as I can feel overwhelmed, but my low neuroticism helps me stay calm and not get too anxious about things. I'm moderately open to new ideas, so I try to keep an open mind when talking about vaccines, even if I hear conflicting views on social media, which I use a few times a week. My high extraversion means I enjoy chatting with friends and family about these topics, but I've learned to be careful. In discussions, I focus on sharing my own experiences, like how getting vaccinated helped me feel safer when visiting my knitting group or going for a bike ride—yes, I still cycle and do yoga to stay active. I avoid pushing my views on others, as my moderate agreeableness makes me want to keep peace. Instead, I ask questions and listen, remembering that everyone has their own reasons. Living in a diverse city like LA, I've met people with all sorts of opinions, and I've found that being patient and kind works best. I don't have children, so I don't have to worry about passing on advice to younger generations, but I do share what I've learned with my married partner. Overall, I believe in managing these discussions by staying informed through reliable sources, respecting others' choices, and focusing on my own health without letting debates upset me too much.",
